вҸә Now I have a thorough understanding of both systems. Here's a brainstorm of how the autoresearch agentic loop pattern could be applied to AI Town:

  ---
  Autoresearch Loop Г— AI Town: Ideas

  The core insight from autoresearch is that the "framework" is just a markdown prompt (program.md) that drives an external AI agent in a plan вҶ’
  execute вҶ’ evaluate вҶ’ keep/revert loop, using git as state management and a single metric as the optimization target. Here's how that pattern maps to
   this project:

  1. Self-Improving NPC Personalities

  The most direct analogue. Write a program.md-style prompt that tells Claude Code to:
  - Pick an NPC personality from data/characters.ts
  - Modify its description/traits
  - Run a scripted conversation scenario via the debug API (POST /scenario, POST /start-convo, advance ticks)
  - Evaluate: Score conversation quality (coherence, personality consistency, engagement) using an LLM-as-judge or a heuristic metric
  - Keep the change if the score improves, git reset if it doesn't
  - Loop forever

  This is nearly identical to autoresearch but the "training script" is the NPC personality definition and the "val_bpb" is a conversation quality
  score.

  2. Prompt Engineering Loop for NPC Providers

  The buildReplyPrompt() function in provider.ts constructs the system prompt sent to LLMs. An autoresearch-style loop could:
  - Modify the prompt template (the one file in scope)
  - Run N conversations via the debug API
  - Measure: response length, memory utilization, personality adherence, conversation naturalness
  - Keep/revert based on a composite score
  - Log results to a TSV

  This would be autonomous prompt optimization вҖ” the agent iterates on the prompt template the same way autoresearch iterates on train.py.

  3. Map & World Tuning

  Use the loop to optimize data/map.json:
  - Modify tile layouts, activity placements, spawn points
  - Run a simulation (spawn NPCs, advance 1000 ticks in stepped mode)
  - Metrics: Average conversations started, path lengths, idle time, coverage of activity locations, dead zones (tiles never visited)
  - Keep layouts that produce more organic-feeling town dynamics

  4. Conversation System Parameter Tuning

  The conversation system in conversation.ts has many tunable constants:
  - Proximity threshold (Manhattan distance вүӨ 6)
  - Max duration (1200 ticks), max messages (20), timeout (600 ticks)
  - Scan interval (20 ticks), cooldown (120 ticks)

  An autoresearch-style loop could sweep these, run simulations, and optimize for metrics like "average meaningful conversations per NPC per 1000
  ticks" or "percentage of time NPCs spend in conversation vs idle."

  5. Memory System Optimization

  The memory scoring weights (Оұ*recency + ОІ*importance + Оі*relevance) and decay rate (0.99) are ripe for autoresearch-style tuning:
  - Modify the weights/decay in memory.ts
  - Run conversation scenarios where NPCs should recall specific things
  - Measure recall accuracy (did the NPC reference the right memory?)
  - Keep/revert

  6. A "Game Director" Agent

  This is the most ambitious idea вҖ” rather than optimizing code, use the loop pattern at runtime as a new kind of orchestrator:
  - Every N ticks, an agent observes the full game state via the debug API
  - Plans an intervention (spawn an NPC, trigger a conversation, place a new activity)
  - Executes via debug API endpoints
  - Evaluates the result (did engagement increase? did something interesting happen?)
  - Logs outcomes and adapts strategy

  This would be a live program.md that runs alongside the game, acting as an autonomous game master.

  7. Pathfinding & Movement Tuning

  The A* implementation and movement speed could be optimized:
  - Modify pathfinding heuristics or movement parameters
  - Run the movement debug harness with various scenarios
  - Measure: path optimality, collision rates, movement smoothness
  - Keep/revert based on a composite movement quality score

  ---
  What Makes This Pattern Transferable

  The key elements from autoresearch that apply here:

